graph title: Nitrogen Balance for Food and Agriculture
description: Nitrogen balance refers to the net difference between Nitrogen inflows and outflows. A good nitrogen balance is slightly positive, ensuring that crops receive enough nitrogen without excessive losses. If nitrogen levels are too high, it can lead to water pollution and greenhouse gas emissions. If too low, soil fertility declines, reducing crop yields.

graph title: Nitrogen Balance for Food and Agriculture [Sources]
description: Nitrogen balance is determined by various sources of nitrogen input and loss in agricultural systems. Commercial application involves adding synthetic fertilizers to the soil to enhance crop growth. Application with manure provides a natural nitrogen source through animal waste. Uptake refers to the process where plants absorb nitrogen from the soil for growth. However, nitrogen can be lost through erosion, leaching, and runoff, where excess nitrogen is washed away by water, leading to pollution. Another loss occurs through denitrification, where soil bacteria convert nitrogen into gas, releasing it into the atmosphere.
plot 3 variable: Nitrogen from Uptake Rate

graph title: Phosphorus Balance in Food and Agriculture
description: Phosphorus balance refers to the net difference between Phosphorus inflows and outflows. A good phosphorus balance is neutral to slightly positive, providing enough phosphorus for crops without excessive buildup. If phosphorus levels are too high, runoff can cause water pollution and algal blooms. If too low, soil fertility declines, leading to lower agricultural productivity.

graph title: Phosphorus Balance for Food and Agriculture [Sources]
description: Phosphorus balance is determined by various inputs and losses in agricultural systems. Commercial application involves adding synthetic phosphorus fertilizers to the soil to enhance plant growth. Application with manure provides a natural source of phosphorus through animal waste. Uptake occurs when plants absorb phosphorus from the soil for growth and development. However, phosphorus can be lost through leaching and runoff, where excess phosphorus is washed away by water, leading to pollution in rivers and lakes.
plot 3 variable: Phosphorus from Uptake Rate

description: The total water required in agriculture comes from two main sources: irrigation and rainfed agriculture. Irrigation water is supplied through artificial methods such as canals, sprinklers, and drip systems to supplement rainfall and ensure consistent crop growth, especially in dry regions. Rainfed agriculture relies entirely on natural rainfall for crop production, making it more vulnerable to climate variability and drought.
